1. With the aim of expansion of the representativeness of desert ecosystems, including the mountaineous subtype of deserts within the PAs system, a consultant has held meetings with local people and decision-makers of 6 districts of Almaty region for establishment of the Arganaty sanctuary and Ile-Balkash reserve. Approval of the decision-makers (at the level of the government of Almaty region) was obtained regarding creation of the wildlife corridor and Arganaty sanctuary; 
2. In line with the goals on assessment of the existing management practice of conservation institutions, identification of correlation between key values of PAs and PA management processes, the PA management effectiveness evaluation methodology was developed. 12 PAs and effectiveness of activities of Altyn Yemel National Park were evaluated as per the METT methodology; 
3. The hired mammalogy expert has prepared the analytical report on the state of key migratory animal species populations and the Action Plan on migratory animal species populations management for implementation of the Programme on migratory animal species populations management in Ile-Balkhash project area;  
4. The review of existing educational programmes has been prepared with the aim to introduce training programmes for students. Project proposals are being prepared to introduce environmental awareness programmes in project areas. 
5. Functional Zonation Atlases were prepared and issued in Kazakh and Russian languages for Ile-Balkhash and Aral-Syrdaria project areas for raising awareness of landscape approach principles
6. 6 grant projects on sustainable agriculture and 2 projects on combating with shifting sands were implemented. As a result, over 20 000 ha of desert pastures are sustainably managed and supplied with water. Living conditions of over 40 people (herders living in the remote rural area) were improved. Mechanical (laying down reed mats) and revegetation (planting of seedlings of hardy-shrub species) works wer

1.	Implementation of works on expansion of the PA system in desert and semi-desert ecosystems of Kazakhstan; 
2.	Adoption of the PA effectiveness evaluation methodology at national level; 
3.	Upgrading the effectiveness of the governance and capacity-building of the staff of pilot and new PAs; 
4.	Development of thematic training modules, training programmes for PA staff. 
5. Continuation of works on demonstration of sand fixation methods in two project areas with the aim to protect settlements from being buried by sands as a measure to combat with the desertification processes; 
6. Demonstration of activities on introducing ecological education in 3 project areas; 
7.	Demonstrating the model of ecological tourism development in Ile-Balkash project area by the example of one pilot farm; 
8.	Conduction of works related to reintroduction and introduction of kulans from Altyn Yemel SNNP to other historical habitats; 
9.	Conduction of works on development and introduction of the geo-portal for space monitoring of desertification and land degradation processes in Aral-Syrdaria and Ile-Balkash project areas with the aim to improve the system of monitoring of the state of desert and semi-desert ecosystems; 
10.	Improvement of material and technical facilities of pilot PAs (procurement of unmanned aerial vehicles) for biodiversity monitoring.  
11.	Testing public committees in pilot territories of protected areas (Altyn_Yemel, Ustyurt, Barsakelmes reserve) acting as a mechanism of involving parties to ensure transparency and planning of PA activities; 
12.	Delivery of workshops, trainings to raise awareness of the wide range of stakeholders and improve the perception of ecosystem services and PES use; 
13.	Monitoring of projects launched in 2016 under the Eco-Damu scheme.

1. Pilot cities for implementation have been identified based on prioritization of cities and their possibilities for participation in the project on low-carbon development.  Memorandums of Understanding have been signed between UNDP and 4 Municipalities Primary analysis of situation on possible investment financing is made;
2. Primary analysis for possibilities to attract investments for low-carbon modernization in urban sector in Kazakhstan cities was made. Based on it, English and Russian publication was issued containing of analysis results, conclusions and recommendations; 
3. 4 inception trainings were arranged and run in pilot cities to familiarize with up-to-date approaches and technologies in identification, development and performance of climate change mitigation measures which are complied with national conditions in urban sector. These measures include the GHG inventory, investing inti effective urban infrastructure, capacity building and increase of awareness among the stakeholders

1. There has been created Task (Working)  Groups for development of low-carbon urban development plans. Alongwith, the statistic date have been compiled for formation of municipal cadaster on CO2 emissions and identification of low-carbon development objectives in the cities. Model of low-carbon urban development has been previously approbated by example of small settlement (Arnasai  village, Akmolinskaya oblast). Experience and lessons leant from this initiative  will be considered by finalization of  above plans in the first half of 2017; 
2. There has been made a classification of low-carbon projects in pilot projects. About 10 pilot projects have been identified and for  5 of these projects there was made a financial and economic calculation: scope of required investments, profitability, discounted payback, etc. Available financial mechanisms (models) have been designed to support the implementation of energy effective initiatives and projects in pilot cities;
3.16 trainings and workshops were conducted in 9 Kazakhstan cities. About 600 people participated in these events: local executive authorities, energy supply companies, small and medium business, servicing companies, banks and etc.

